User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 22, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 43 responses, 15 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 35% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience and neuroscience. Within these broad areas, several specific subfields are prominent, including:

  • Mental Health: This includes research on mental disorders (general), psychotherapy, mood and psychotic disorders, child and adolescent psychiatry, anorexia nervosa, and brain development related to mental health.
  • Aging & Dementia: A significant portion of respondents focus on aging, dementia, cerebrovascular disease, and healthy aging, often with an emphasis on cognitive and motor function.
  • Brain Injury & Rehabilitation: Research on brain injury (including sport-related) and rehabilitation medicine is also represented.
  • Language & Communication: Several respondents focus on cognitive neuroscience of language, bilingualism, speech and language processing, and auditory processing.
  • Neurological Disorders: Including Multiple Sclerosis, Parkinson’s, ADHD, and other neurological conditions.
  • Women’s Health: A focus on women’s health, menopause, aging cognition, and diseases/symptoms related to the menstrual cycle.

Other areas of interest include:

  • Decision-making
  • Autoimmunity
  • Pain
  • Music cognition
  • Body image
  • Impulse Control
  • Environmental Psychology
  • Paleoclimatology

In summary, the responses indicate a wide-ranging interest in the brain and its functions, with a particular concentration in areas related to cognitive processes, neurological and psychiatric conditions, and the impact of aging.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, expanded access to MRI would significantly improve and broaden research in several key areas:

  • Brain Structure and Function: A core theme is using MRI to study the brain’s structure, function, and connectivity across the lifespan, in both healthy individuals and those with neurological, psychiatric, or other disorders. This includes understanding cognitive processes like memory, attention, and emotional regulation. Many researchers emphasized the current limitations on their ability to adequately explore these areas without better MRI access.
  • Mechanisms of Disease and Treatment: Researchers want to use MRI to investigate the underlying mechanisms of various conditions, including sexual dysfunctions, Lupus Nephritis, eating disorders, neurodevelopmental disorders, pain, multiple sclerosis (MS), and brain-related injuries. This includes studying inflammatory changes, brain activity during specific tasks, and the effects of interventions (e.g., non-invasive brain stimulation, hormonal treatments, clinical trials).
  • Age-Related Changes: Several researchers focus on how brain structure and function change with age and in association with hormone variations and menopause. This includes studying the relationship between brain changes and cognitive/motor decline.
  • Specific Populations and Conditions: There’s a desire to use MRI to study specific populations, such as those with ADHD (particularly women), bilingual individuals, dementia patients, those with concussion and those in Northern Norway where access is particularly limited. The goal is to identify biomarkers, understand sex differences, and develop individualized treatment approaches.
  • Technological Advancement and Method Development: Improved access would facilitate method development and testing novel algorithms, enhancing the precision and reproducibility of findings.
  • Collaboration and Larger Studies: Many researchers highlighted that better access would enable them to participate in multi-center studies, increasing sample sizes and statistical power. Improved access would also enable them to run large and small-scale studies.
  • Funding and Career Advancement: Lack of access is currently hindering researchers from gaining necessary experience and publishing in neuroimaging, which is impacting their ability to secure funding.
  • Novel Research Areas: Researchers are interested in using MRI to explore new areas such as the neurobiology of sexual arousal, the interaction between the brain and artificial agents, and the detection of geohazards in geological archives.
  • Improving Clinical Practice: A key component of access to MRI is it is ability to give clinical relevant information for making decisions, and tracking of disease progression.
  • Education and Training: Increased accessibility would help to train the next generation of researchers through Master’s and PhD Theses.

Overall, the survey highlights that improved MRI access would be a catalyst for significant advancements in neuroscience, clinical research, and our understanding of the human brain, and lead to improvements in health outcomes. The lack of reliable access is currently a major impediment to progress. The organizational and financial barriers associated with the MRI are the most important.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Survey respondents highlighted the need for dedicated research MRI resources, suggesting the establishment of a research-focused scanner outside of hospital settings, preferably closer to the University of Bergen campus. They also emphasized prioritizing research over clinical use on existing scanners. Furthermore, respondents expressed a desire for more affordable pricing for research MRI access and strongly advocated for the creation of a collaborative MRI research community in Tromsø to foster knowledge sharing and project development. Finally, the initiative that prompted the survey was positively received.

Conclusion

The findings of this survey resoundingly underscore the urgent and unmet need for increased access to dedicated research-focused MRI scanners in Norway. The responses, representing a diverse cross-section of researchers from universities and hospitals across the country, consistently highlight how limited scanner availability currently stifles research progress, hinders collaboration, and even forces researchers to seek resources abroad. The potential impact of increased MRI capacity is substantial, promising to unlock new avenues of investigation into a wide range of critical areas, from cognitive neuroscience and mental health to neurodegenerative diseases and innovative treatment strategies. Beyond simply increasing the number of scanners, respondents emphasized the critical importance of dedicated research scanners, access to which is managed by trained scientists, and that are not subject to the competing demands of clinical use. The compelling testimonials within this survey paint a clear picture: investing in expanded MRI research infrastructure is not just a matter of facilitating individual projects, but of strengthening the entire Norwegian research ecosystem, attracting top talent, and ultimately driving innovation that benefits the health and well-being of the nation. We, therefore, strongly recommend that these results be used to inform strategic investment decisions that prioritize the acquisition and effective management of more research-dedicated MRI scanners across Norway, enabling Norwegian scientists to realize their full potential and contribute groundbreaking advancements to the field. The time for action is now; the future of Norwegian neuroscience research depends on it.
